S. Africa Stocks: Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Avusa, Richemont

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-04-26T13:47:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/s-africa-stocks-anglo-american-bhp-billiton-avusa-richemont.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index fluctuated. The index gained 20.25, or 0.1 percent,
to 32,679.11 at 3:15 p.m. in Johannesburg after falling as much
as 0.3 percent earlier.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified miner, which
makes up 11 percent of the index, declined 5.08 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 347.42 rand. Copper fell the most in seven weeks and
platinum dropped for the first day in five.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, slid 2.91 rand, or 1 percent, to 281.12 rand.  Avusa Ltd. (AVU)  , the owner of South Africa’s biggest
newspaper rose 50 cents, or 2.1 percent, to 24.50 rand. The
Public Investment Corp., which owns 9.3 percent of Avusa, said
an offer price of 26 rand per share for Avusa by Capitau
Holdings Ltd. and its partners is too low.  Cie. Financiere Richemont SA (CFR SJ), the maker of Cartier
and Piaget watches gained 44 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 42.20
rand. Swiss watch exports rose 16.5 percent in March from a year
before, the Federation of the Swiss Watch Industry reported.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Robert Brand in  Cape Town  at 
 rbrand9@bloomberg.net   To contact the editors responsible for this story: Gavin Serkin
at   gserkin@bloomberg.net . 